{
  "texts": [
    "Yu and Fazekas (2023) are an exception-they used an L 2 waveform loss to highlight the ability of their differentiable source-filter approach to reconstruct phase.",
    "Most commonly reported are distances computed between timefrequency representations of audio signals, sometimes referred to as spectral error.",
    "Multi-scale spectrogram error, which is often also used as a loss function, was reported in a number of music (Masuda and Saito, 2021; Wu D.-Y. et al., 2022; Renault et al., 2022; Shan et al., 2022), singing (Yu and Fazekas, 2023), and speech evaluations (Nercessian, 2021).",
    "Other spectral distances reported included logspectral distance Masuda and Saito (2021); Subramani et al. (2022), log mel-spectral distance Nercessian (2023), and mel-cepstrum distortion (MCD) (Masuda and Saito, 2023).",
    "Similarity metrics motivated by perception, such as the Perceptual Evaluation of Speech Quality (PESQ) (International Telecommunication Union, 2001) were developed as alternatives to costly subjective evaluations."
  ]
}